1
00:00:00,950 --> 00:00:04,590
We've developed a reinforcement
learning formalism

2
00:00:04,590 --> 00:00:08,310
using the six state
Mars rover example.

3
00:00:08,310 --> 00:00:11,640
Let's do a quick review of
the key concepts and also see

4
00:00:11,640 --> 00:00:13,470
how this set of concepts can be

5
00:00:13,470 --> 00:00:15,990
used for other
applications as well.

6
00:00:15,990 --> 00:00:18,855
Some of the concepts
we've discussed

7
00:00:18,855 --> 00:00:22,730
are states of a reinforcement
learning problem,

8
00:00:22,730 --> 00:00:26,025
the set of actions, the rewards,

9
00:00:26,025 --> 00:00:28,830
a discount factor,
then how rewards and

10
00:00:28,830 --> 00:00:30,450
the discount factor altogether

11
00:00:30,450 --> 00:00:32,280
use to compute the return,

12
00:00:32,280 --> 00:00:35,550
and then finally, a
policy whose job it

13
00:00:35,550 --> 00:00:39,030
is to help you pick actions
so as to maximize the return.

14
00:00:39,030 --> 00:00:40,800
For the Mars rover example,

15
00:00:40,800 --> 00:00:43,320
we had six states
that we numbered

16
00:00:43,320 --> 00:00:48,270
1-6 and the actions were
to go left or to go right.

17
00:00:48,270 --> 00:00:51,920
The rewards were 100
for the leftmost state,

18
00:00:51,920 --> 00:00:53,720
40 for the rightmost state,

19
00:00:53,720 --> 00:00:55,450
and zero in between

20
00:00:55,450 --> 00:00:59,420
and I was using a
discount factor of 0.5.

21
00:00:59,420 --> 00:01:03,320
The return was given by this
formula and we could have

22
00:01:03,320 --> 00:01:05,105
different policies Pi depict

23
00:01:05,105 --> 00:01:07,670
actions depending on
what state you're in.

24
00:01:07,670 --> 00:01:10,580
This same formalism
or states, actions,

25
00:01:10,580 --> 00:01:12,050
rewards, and so on can be used

26
00:01:12,050 --> 00:01:14,195
for many other
applications as well.

27
00:01:14,195 --> 00:01:17,945
Take the problem or find
an autonomous helicopter.

28
00:01:17,945 --> 00:01:21,080
To set a state
would be the set of

29
00:01:21,080 --> 00:01:23,570
possible positions
and orientations and

30
00:01:23,570 --> 00:01:26,255
speeds and so on
of the helicopter.

31
00:01:26,255 --> 00:01:29,240
The possible actions
would be the set of

32
00:01:29,240 --> 00:01:30,665
possible ways to move

33
00:01:30,665 --> 00:01:32,870
the controls stick
of a helicopter,

34
00:01:32,870 --> 00:01:36,875
and the rewards may be a plus
one if it's flying well,

35
00:01:36,875 --> 00:01:38,645
and a negative 1,000

36
00:01:38,645 --> 00:01:41,140
if it doesn't fall
really bad or crashes.

37
00:01:41,140 --> 00:01:42,825
Reward function that tells you

38
00:01:42,825 --> 00:01:45,015
how well the
helicopter is flying.

39
00:01:45,015 --> 00:01:47,030
The discount factor, a number

40
00:01:47,030 --> 00:01:49,160
slightly less than
one maybe say,

41
00:01:49,160 --> 00:01:51,350
0.99 and then based

42
00:01:51,350 --> 00:01:53,375
on the rewards and
the discount factor,

43
00:01:53,375 --> 00:01:57,620
you compute the return
using the same formula.

44
00:01:57,620 --> 00:01:59,690
The job of a
reinforcement learning

45
00:01:59,690 --> 00:02:01,400
algorithm would be to find

46
00:02:01,400 --> 00:02:05,540
some policy Pi of s so
that given as input,

47
00:02:05,540 --> 00:02:07,430
the position of
the helicopter s,

48
00:02:07,430 --> 00:02:09,740
it tells you what
action to take.

49
00:02:09,740 --> 00:02:12,500
That is, tells you how to
move the control sticks.

50
00:02:12,500 --> 00:02:13,815
Here's one more example.

51
00:02:13,815 --> 00:02:15,155
Here's a game-playing one.

52
00:02:15,155 --> 00:02:16,340
Say you want to use

53
00:02:16,340 --> 00:02:18,875
reinforcement learning
to learn to play chess.

54
00:02:18,875 --> 00:02:21,380
The state of this problem would

55
00:02:21,380 --> 00:02:24,400
be the position of all
the pieces on the board.

56
00:02:24,400 --> 00:02:27,545
By the way, if you play chess
and know the rules well,

57
00:02:27,545 --> 00:02:30,485
I know that's little
bit more information

58
00:02:30,485 --> 00:02:31,700
than just the position of

59
00:02:31,700 --> 00:02:33,470
the pieces is
important for chess,

60
00:02:33,470 --> 00:02:36,170
but I'll simplify it a
little bit for this video.

61
00:02:36,170 --> 00:02:40,505
The actions are the possible
legal moves in the game,

62
00:02:40,505 --> 00:02:44,000
and then a common choice
of reward would be if you

63
00:02:44,000 --> 00:02:47,705
give your system a reward of
plus one if it wins a game,

64
00:02:47,705 --> 00:02:50,105
minus one if it loses the game,

65
00:02:50,105 --> 00:02:53,510
and a reward of zero
if it ties a game.

66
00:02:53,510 --> 00:02:56,990
For chess, usually
a discount factor

67
00:02:56,990 --> 00:02:58,700
very close to one will be used,

68
00:02:58,700 --> 00:03:02,910
so maybe 0.99 or even 0.995 or

69
00:03:02,910 --> 00:03:05,810
0.999 and the return

70
00:03:05,810 --> 00:03:08,495
uses the same formula as
the other applications.

71
00:03:08,495 --> 00:03:12,470
Once again, the goal is given

72
00:03:12,470 --> 00:03:17,885
a board position to pick a
good action using a policy Pi.

73
00:03:17,885 --> 00:03:21,890
This formalism of a reinforcement
learning application

74
00:03:21,890 --> 00:03:23,420
actually has a name.

75
00:03:23,420 --> 00:03:26,465
It's called a Markov
decision process,

76
00:03:26,465 --> 00:03:27,590
and I know that sounds like

77
00:03:27,590 --> 00:03:29,810
a big technical
complicated term.

78
00:03:29,810 --> 00:03:33,170
But if you ever hear this
term Markov decision process

79
00:03:33,170 --> 00:03:36,090
or MDP for short,

80
00:03:36,090 --> 00:03:38,090
that's just the formalism
that we've been

81
00:03:38,090 --> 00:03:40,340
talking about in the
last few videos.

82
00:03:40,340 --> 00:03:43,430
The term Markov in the MDP or

83
00:03:43,430 --> 00:03:47,150
Markov decision process
refers to that the future

84
00:03:47,150 --> 00:03:50,510
only depends on the current
state and not on anything

85
00:03:50,510 --> 00:03:52,070
that might have occurred prior

86
00:03:52,070 --> 00:03:54,035
to getting to the current state.

87
00:03:54,035 --> 00:03:57,290
In other words, in a
Markov decision process,

88
00:03:57,290 --> 00:04:00,380
the future depends only
on where you are now,

89
00:04:00,380 --> 00:04:02,335
not on how you got here.

90
00:04:02,335 --> 00:04:03,995
One other way to think of

91
00:04:03,995 --> 00:04:07,160
the Markov decision
process formalism is

92
00:04:07,160 --> 00:04:10,655
that we have a robot or

93
00:04:10,655 --> 00:04:13,400
some other agent that

94
00:04:13,400 --> 00:04:16,515
we wish to control
and what we get to do

95
00:04:16,515 --> 00:04:23,360
is choose actions a and
based on those actions,

96
00:04:23,360 --> 00:04:28,145
something will happen in the
world or in the environment,

97
00:04:28,145 --> 00:04:31,040
such as our position in
the world changes or we

98
00:04:31,040 --> 00:04:32,330
get to sample a piece of

99
00:04:32,330 --> 00:04:34,535
rock and execute the
science mission.

100
00:04:34,535 --> 00:04:36,950
The way we choose
the action a is with

101
00:04:36,950 --> 00:04:41,205
a policy Pi and based on
what happens in the world,

102
00:04:41,205 --> 00:04:43,280
we then get to see or we

103
00:04:43,280 --> 00:04:46,010
observe back what
state we're in,

104
00:04:46,010 --> 00:04:51,275
as well as what rewards
are that we get.

105
00:04:51,275 --> 00:04:54,920
You sometimes see different
authors use a diagram like

106
00:04:54,920 --> 00:04:58,610
this to represent the
Markov decision process or

107
00:04:58,610 --> 00:05:02,045
the MDP formalism but this
is just another way of

108
00:05:02,045 --> 00:05:04,070
illustrating the set of concepts

109
00:05:04,070 --> 00:05:06,170
that you learn about in
the last few videos.

110
00:05:06,170 --> 00:05:11,120
You now know how a reinforcement
learning problem works.

111
00:05:11,120 --> 00:05:13,580
In the next video
we'll start to develop

112
00:05:13,580 --> 00:05:16,210
an algorithm for
picking good actions.

113
00:05:16,210 --> 00:05:19,370
The first step toward that
will be to define and then

114
00:05:19,370 --> 00:05:20,795
eventually learn to compute

115
00:05:20,795 --> 00:05:23,000
the state action value function.

116
00:05:23,000 --> 00:05:25,850
This turns out to be one
of the key quantities

117
00:05:25,850 --> 00:05:29,065
for when we want to develop
a learning algorithm.

118
00:05:29,065 --> 00:05:32,120
Let's go onto the next
video to see what is this,

119
00:05:32,120 --> 00:05:35,100
